PART L — Hardware Registers

Q25 Why avoid bitfields for hardware?
Because bit order may vary.
Use masks:
reg |= (1 << 0);if(reg & (1 << 1))

PART M — Memory Optimization

Q26 How reduce padding?
Order large to small:
double → int → short → char

PART N — Golden Rules

Rule 1
Each member starts at valid aligned offset.

Rule 2
Struct size rounded to multiple of largest alignment.

Rule 3
Bitfields use implementation-defined packing.

Rule 4
Same type often shares storage unit.

Rule 5
Mixed bitfield types may vary by compiler.

Final Super Summary
Padding = empty bytesAlignment = valid address boundaryOffset = position from startBitfield = bit-sized memberBase type = type controlling storage unit

Most Important Correction
